              <span class="stat-label">Guests per booking</span>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h2 id="no-principal-residence">No Principal Residence Requirement</h2>
          <p>This is the big one. <strong>Kingston does not require your STR to be your principal residence.</strong> This makes it one of the few Ontario cities where you can legally Airbnb an investment property.</p>

          <div class="success-box">
            <h4>What This Means for Investors</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You can STR a property you don't live in</li>
              <li>You can hold up to <strong>2 STR licenses</strong> as an individual</li>
              <li>Corporate officers and directors can each hold licenses too</li>
              <li>No need to claim the property as your home</li>
              <li>Ideal for out-of-town investors looking at the Kingston market</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p>Compare this to Toronto, Mississauga, Brampton, Ottawa, and most other Ontario cities where principal residence is mandatory. Kingston stands out as genuinely investor-friendly, similar to Sault Ste. Marie.</p>

          <h3>The 2-License Limit</h3>
          <p>There is one restriction: you can't hold more than 2 licenses.</p>

          <blockquote class="bylaw-quote">
            "An Operator shall not hold more than two (2) Licences and shall not operate or permit the operation of more than two (2) Short-term Rentals at any time, either individually as a natural person or as an officer or director of a corporation that holds a Licence."
            <cite>Kingston Bylaw 2021-10, Section 5.2</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <p>If you had licenses before July 2022 (when this limit was introduced), you can keep them as long as you renew without lapse. But new operators are capped at 2 properties.</p>

          <h2 id="license-requirements">License Requirements</h2>
          <p>You must have a valid license before marketing or operating any STR in Kingston. Here's what you need:</p>

          <h3>To Get Licensed</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Complete application</strong> in the form prescribed by the Director</li>
            <li><strong>Pay the license fee</strong> (check Kingston's Fees and Charges Bylaw for current rates)</li>
            <li><strong>Property compliance</strong> with zoning, building code, and fire code</li>
            <li><strong>No outstanding debts</strong> to the city (fines, property taxes, MAT)</li>
            <li><strong>No active orders</strong> from Building, Fire, Health Unit, or Environment Ministry</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="callout">
            <div class="callout-icon">
              <svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
                <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle>
                <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
                <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
              </svg>
            </div>
            <div class="callout-content">
              <strong>Inspection may be required:</strong> The Director can require an inspection of your property before issuing or renewing a license. All issues must be fixed before you get approved.
            </div>
          </div>

          <h3>License Display Requirements</h3>
          <p>Once licensed, you must:</p>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Post the physical license</strong> in a prominent place near the entry</li>
            <li><strong>Include your license number</strong> in all listings and marketing materials</li>
            <li><strong>Provide the city</strong> with links to your online listings</li>
            <li><strong>Display emergency contact info</strong> for guests prominently in the rental</li>
          </ol>

          <h2 id="occupancy-limits">Occupancy Limits</h2>
          <p>Kingston has clear occupancy rules to prevent party houses and overcrowding:</p>

          <div class="comparison-table">
            <div class="comparison-header">
              <div class="comparison-col">Rental Type</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Occupancy Limit</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Entire unit rental</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Max 2 per bedroom, 10 total</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Room-by-room rental</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Max 3 rooms, 4 guests total</div>
            </div>
            <div class="comparison-row">
              <div class="comparison-col">Children under 2</div>
              <div class="comparison-col highlight">Don't count toward limit</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <blockquote class="bylaw-quote">
            "No Operator shall permit more than two (2) occupants in each bedroom within a Short-term Rental...and no Operator shall permit more than ten (10) occupants rented under a single booking."
            <cite>Kingston Bylaw 2021-10, Section 7.2</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <p>For room rentals specifically: if you're renting rooms individually (like a hostel model), you're capped at 3 rooms with a maximum of 4 guests in aggregate. This prevents operators from cramming guests into every available space.</p>

          <h2 id="mat-tax">Municipal Accommodation Tax (MAT)</h2>
          <p>Kingston has a Municipal Accommodation Tax that applies to short-term rentals. Under Bylaw 2018-95, operators must:</p>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Collect MAT</strong> from guests on all bookings under 30 days</li>
            <li><strong>Remit the tax</strong> to the city as required</li>
            <li><strong>Keep records</strong> of all MAT collected for 3 years</li>
          </ul>

          <div class="warning-box">
            <h4>Verify Platform Collection</h4>
            <p>Some platforms like Airbnb may collect and remit MAT automatically, but confirm this with the City of Kingston. If you take direct bookings or use platforms that don't collect automatically, you're responsible for collecting and remitting the tax yourself.</p>
          </div>

          <h2 id="compliance">Staying Compliant</h2>
          <p>Kingston takes enforcement seriously. Here's how to stay on the right side of the bylaw:</p>

          <h3>Record Keeping (3 Years)</h3>
          <p>You must keep detailed records for at least 3 years after each transaction:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Number of nights rented</li>
            <li>Nightly and total price charged</li>
            <li>Total MAT collected</li>
            <li>Whether it was entire-unit or partial-unit</li>
            <li>Any other information the Director requests</li>
          </ul>

          <p>The city can request these records, and you have <strong>30 days to produce them</strong>. Set up a system from day one. A spreadsheet works, or use your platform's transaction history.</p>

          <h3>Notify the City of Changes</h3>
          <p>If anything changes from your original application, you must notify the city within 14 days and provide updated documentation. This includes contact info, property details, or ownership changes.</p>

          <h3>Parking Compliance</h3>
          <p>Your STR must comply with parking requirements in Kingston's Zoning Bylaw and Parking Bylaw 2010-128. Make sure you have adequate parking for guests and include parking instructions in your listing.</p>

          <h2 id="penalties">Penalties for Non-Compliance</h2>
          <p>Kingston uses both administrative penalties and provincial offences for enforcement:</p>

          <div class="penalty-box">
            <h4>Penalty Structure</h4>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Administrative penalties</strong> per the city's Administrative Penalty Process Bylaw</li>
              <li><strong>Provincial offences</strong> with fines of <strong>$500 to $10,000 per day</strong></li>
              <li><strong>Continuing offences</strong> mean each day of violation is a separate offence</li>
              <li><strong>Director/officer liability</strong> for corporate operators</li>
              <li><strong>Cost recovery</strong> for city enforcement actions added to your tax bill</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <p>The city can also revoke or suspend your license, and unpaid fines can be added to your property tax roll. Don't risk it.</p>

          <h2 id="bed-and-breakfast">Bed and Breakfast Rules</h2>
          <p>B&Bs fall under the same licensing bylaw but have specific requirements:</p>

          <blockquote class="bylaw-quote">
            "Bed and Breakfast means an operator-occupied detached dwelling offering short-term lodging for compensation to the travelling and vacationing public, which guest rooms or suites may include a private bath, but do not include cooking facilities."
            <cite>Kingston Bylaw 2021-10, Part 1 Definitions</cite>
          </blockquote>

          <h3>B&B Requirements</h3>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Must be owner-occupied</strong> (you live there)</li>
            <li><strong>Detached dwelling</strong> only</li>
            <li><strong>No cooking facilities</strong> in guest rooms</li>
            <li><strong>Private bath</strong> is allowed</li>
            <li><strong>Cannot operate alongside</strong> a regular STR in the same unit</li>
          </ul>

          <p>If you're running a traditional B&B with breakfast service and you live on-site, this is your category. You still need the STR license.</p>

          <h2 id="official-resources">Official City of Kingston Resources</h2>
          <p>Always verify current requirements with official sources:</p>

          <div class="resources-box">
            <h4>Official Links</h4>
            <ul>
